Togolese law protects the rights to family planning, however, it only covers public sector providers. Abortion can only be legally carried out in Togo if there is risk to the life of the mother. In October, it was reported that three health workers were charged with aggravated aggravated homicide – a charge that was rarely, if ever, applied in Togo – in relation with the death of a pregnant woman. The charges are unprecedented and raising concerns among human right defenders in Togo over the right to maternity and the safety of women in the country.

Despite fears around the prosecution of the health workers, the Togolese authories undertook to ensure the penal prosecution of every woman who would request abortion. Dozens of abortion providers have been “arrested” in hospitals and subjected to penal investigation, since June 10, without considering the gravity and real reason for an abortion, such as the pregnancy of an underage girl or a rape victim, ignored by the prosecution.
